<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
  <title></title>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles/vendor/bulma/css/bulma.css">
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles/site.css">
</head>

<body>
  <section class="hero is-info is-large">
    <div class="hero-body">
      <div class="container">
        <h1 class="title is-1">
          Custom Elements Everywhere
        </h1>
        <h2 class="subtitle is-4">
          Making sure frameworks and custom elements can be BFFs
          <span class="cheers">üçª</span>
        </h2>
      </div>
    </div>
    {{>octocat}}
  </section>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="columns">
        <div class="column is-two-thirds">
          <div class="content">
            <h2 class="title is-2">What's this?</h2>
            <p>
              Custom Elements are the lynchpin in the Web Components specifications. They give developers the ability to define their own
              HTML elements, which, when coupled with Shadow DOM, should be able to work in any application.
            </p>
            <p>
              But reality can sometimes prove otherwise. Often when developers try to incorporate Custom Elements into their apps, they
              run into interoperability issues with their chosen framework or library. These issues could arise from a number
              of different sources: disagreements about how data should be passed, polyfill quirks, different style scoping
              strategies, etc.
            </p>
            <p>
              This project runs a suite of tests against each framework to determine how they render and communicate with Custom Elements.
              The goal is to both identify interoperability issues, and highlight potential fixes already implemented in
              other frameworks. Ultimately, if frameworks agree on <em>how</em> they will communicate with
              Custom Elements, it makes developers jobs easier as they can author their elements to meet these expectations.
            </p>
            <p>
              Lastly, it's important to note that sometimes the expected behavior is not always clear. The tests in this project are a
              best guess as to how things should work, but are by no means final. Driving discussion and finding consensus
              is also a primary goal of this project so don't be afraid to open a GitHub issue to discuss places where the
              tests could be improved. ‚úåÔ∏è
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {{#each libraries}}
    <section class="section">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="columns">
          <div class="column">
            <div class="columns">
              <div class="column">
                <div class="level">
                  <div class="level-left">
                    <div class="level-item">
                      <h2 class="title is-2">{{capitalize name}}</h2>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="level-right">
                    <div class="level-item">
                      <div>
                        <p class="heading has-text-centered">Score</p>
                        <p class="title">{{results.success}}/{{results.total}}</p>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <progress class="progress is-primary" value="{{results.percent}}" max="100">{{results.percent}}%</progress>
                <div class="content">
                  {{{summary.content}}}
                </div>
                <div class="content">
                  <a class="button is-info is-outlined" href="libraries/{{name}}/results.html">
                    View the tests
                  </a>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="column is-offset-1">
                <div class="box">
                  <h3 class="title is-3">Related Issues</h3>
                  {{#if issues}}
                    {{#each issues}}
                      <article class="media">
                        <div class="media-content">
                          <a href="{{link}}">
                            <div class="content">
                              <p>
                                <strong>{{title}}</strong>
                                <br>
                                <small>{{meta}}</small>
                              </p>
                            </div>
                          </a>
                        </div>
                      </article>
                    {{/each}}
                    {{else}}
                      <div class="has-text-centered">
                        <img src="images/smiley.svg" alt="" width="256">
                        <h4 class="title is-4 no-issues-caption">Yay! No open issues!</h4>
                      </div>
                  {{/if}}
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  {{/each}}
</body>

</html>
